NEGOTIATIONS between the government and an investor for the implementation of the Mchuchuma and Liganga power projects are at final stages as the government insists that it will in the next financial year 2022/23 it will initiate fresh valuation and pay compensation to people who will vacate their areas to pave the way for the implementation of the vital projects. Deputy Minister for Industries, Trade and Investment, Mr Exhaud Kigahe told the National Assembly yesterday that the robust project is expected to create employment at the same time helping small scale miners. He was responding to a supplementary question by Ludewa Member of Parliament Joseph Kamonga (CCM) who wanted the artisanal miners to be allowed to continue with their activities at the project site as the government continues with talks with the government. In his response Mr Kigahe said all was well, insisting that in the implementation of the Mchuchuma and Liganga project which aim to produce coal and iron, the government would ensure that local content was observed. During his main question, Mr Kamonga wanted to know when the government would pay compensation to Ludewa residents whose land was confiscated to pave the way for the construction of mega industries at the areas of Mchuchuma and Liganga. Responding, the minister said during 2022/23 fiscal year the government would conduct valuation and pay all residents their compensation. The Mchuchuma and Liganga power project sare expected to be implemented in a joint venture between the government through the National Development Corporation (NDC) on behalf of the government and a private company (shareholder), although he fell short of revealing the name.